  "market_context": "The case analyzes the US100 (Nasdaq-100) daily chart during the March 2020 COVID-19 market crash and subsequent recovery, spanning from December 2019 to June 2020.",
  "key_observation": "The analyst observed how different moving averages (SMA, EMA, HMA, ALMA) and MACD reacted differently to the sharp crash and reversal, with HMA being most responsive but prone to false signals, while ALMA provided smoother trend adherence.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: The analyst introduced the US100 daily chart showing the March 2020 crash and recovery as the core example for comparing moving averages.",
    "Step 2: The analyst added and configured SMA 20 and SMA 100 to observe their lagging behavior during the crash and recovery phases.",
    "Step 3: The analyst replaced SMAs with EMA 20 and compared its faster reaction to price changes versus SMA 20 during both the crash and the rebound.",
    "Step 4: The analyst added HMA 50 and demonstrated its superior responsiveness and smoothness compared to SMA 50 and EMA 50, noting it reacted earliest to the crash and reversal but generated false breakouts.",
    "Step 5: The analyst added ALMA 50 (window size 50, offset 0.85, sigma 6) and compared it with HMA 50, highlighting ALMA’s smoother trend-following and fewer false signals despite slightly slower reaction.",
    "Step 6: The analyst added MACD (12,26,9) and explained its construction (EMA12 - EMA26 for MACD line, EMA9 of MACD for signal line), showing how its peaks/valleys reflected bearish then bullish momentum during the crash and recovery."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Moving average choice involves trade-offs: HMA offers speed but more false signals; ALMA offers smoothness and better trend respect; EMA balances responsiveness and reliability; MACD captures momentum shifts but requires deeper study. Combining with market structure improves trade quality.",
